==English==
===Alternative spellings===
*[[cat's pajamas]]  ''(US)''

===Etymology===
An [[English language|English]] slang phrase coined by [[w:Thomas A. Dorgan]]. The phrase means "the height of [[excellence]]" and became popular in the [[U.S.]] in the [[w:1920s]],<ref>http://www.randomhouse.com/wotd/index.pperl?date=20010102</ref> along with [[bee's knees]],  "the cat's whiskers" (possibly from the use of these in radio crystal sets), and similar phrases that didn't endure:  "the eel's ankle", "the elephant's instep", "the snake's hip" and "the [[capybara|capybara's]] spats".<ref>Mark Israel, 'Phrase Origins: "The bee's knees"' alt.usage.english FAQ file,(line 4407), (29 Sept 1997).  http://www.exw6sxq.com/sparky/aue_related/full_faq.html </ref>

===Idiom===
'''[[the]] [[cat]][['s]] [[pyjamas]]''' ('''pajamas*''')
# {{idiom}} A highly [[sought-after]] and [[fancy]] example of something, usually [[referring]] to [[inanimate]] [[objects]]. 
#* That new car was really '''the cat's pyjamas.'''

====Synonyms====
*[[the bee's knees]]
*[[the cat's meow]]
<!--* the cat's nuts ''(American slang)'' disputed. -->

====Spelling note====
*British usage is '''pyjamas''' while American is '''pajamas'''

